From : {bold}JoNty{nobold} <jonty_amiga@ntlworld.com>
{p} {p}
Hello Paul
{p} {p}
In  response  to  your  reply to "A1200 Ressurrection" in the December 2000
issue of AIO.
{p} {p}
You said that with a 030, DOOM would be sluggish.  Sorry but it isn`t.  :)
{p} {p}
I  have  a Magnum Mk 3 (Apollo) 030@40 Mhz FPU and 16 meg of fast mem and I
get  a considerably playable speed with DOOMAttack tested with all the main
WADs,  full  screen with visible info bar, low detial, in CGXNTSC:  Low Res
with  such  programs  running as SetMan, CMQ030, StackAttack, QBC, BlazeWCP
and  FBlit running with CPUControl enabled caches, FastROM and MOVEVBR, and
replacement  faster  math  libs  (not sure if DOOMAttack uses the math libs
though) installed.
{p} {p}
-={p}
JoNty (jonty_amiga@ntlworld.com)
{p} {p}
{bold}Paul's Reply :{nobold}{p}
Hello JoNty,
{p} {p}
Well, it looks as if I could have been a bit hasty saying the 030 was
a bit sluggish in running doom. The key words here are "a bit". I used
to spend hours trying to finish Doom on my A1200, which had a CSA 12
guage 50Mhz 030 & '882, + 16MB of 70ns FP RAM. With full screen, full
detail, the frame rate hovered close to 10 FPS with the Doom 2 wads
and ADoom. Most of the time, in big levels, I had to run it in low
detail to make it enjoyable. I have heard reports that DoomAttack is
faster than ADoom, but judging by the poor performance of my
A4000ec030 @ 25Mhz with ADoom, and the fact I have a much more capable
PC to run Doom, I decided that on average, Doom is "a bit" sluggish on
030 systems. Of course, everyone's mileage will vary (especially with
the patches you've mentioned), and different people tolerate
different frame rates.
{p} {p}
I might just add that my A4000 is still my main computer (I've done
two commercial web sites with it now), and whilst it is "a bit"
painful doing the graphics work with an ec030, the CV64-3D makes it
all possible, and my PC is used purely for games, previewing my
work with IE 4, Netscape 4.72, and Opera 3.60, and a bit of work with
Delphi. So until I decide whether to buy a fast 040 or take the plunge
and get a PPC board, my Amiga will still be "a bit" sluggish :).
{p} {p}
- Paul
{p} {p}
