From : {bold}Gary Machon{nobold} <gary.studio@gtonline.net>
{p} {p}
I have been using AMIGA for many years now and have been running the
brilliant MUSIC X sequencer.
{p} {p}
I am now trying to set up a PC based system but cannot find any sequencer
that I like as much as MUSIC X
{p} {p}
Is there anybody who has converted MUCIC X for PC use?  If so, do you know
where I can get it?
{p} {p}
Hoping you can help
{p} {p}
Gary Machon{p}
Guernsey
{p} {p}
{bold}Paul's reply :{nobold}
{p} {p}
Hello Gary,
{p} {p}
Unfortunately, after doing a little searching, it seems that Music X
stopped development long ago (Perhaps '94?). In the review for Music X
2.0 on aminet, (see {link http://aminet.net/aminet/dirs/aminet/docs/rview/MusicX2.0.txt}http://aminet.net/aminet/dirs/aminet/docs/rview/MusicX2.0.txt{end}, there
is a snippet of an email correspondance with the original author, who
says he traded Music X 2.0 to Hollyware in return for the rights to
some of his other products, when MicroIllusions was bought. If there
has been any more development (I haven't seen any signs of that at
all), it wasn't by the original author.
{p} {p}
On the bright side, there are dozens of popular sequencers on PC.
Obviously, it will take some getting used to, after using Music X
for all these years, but I hear good words about Cakewalk
(www.cakewalk.com), Audition ({link http://www.bowrad.ndirect.co.uk}link http://www.bowrad.ndirect.co.uk{end}), and
Massiva ({link http://home.c2i.net/jaase/massiva.htm}home.c2i.net/jaase/massiva.htm{end}).  I know Bars & Pipes is
fairly well known on PC, but I think it's not generally regarded as a
professional midi sequencer. I'm not very familiar with midi
sequencing though, so I guess your best bet would be to look
around and talk to someone who knows their stuff and see what they
think.
{p} {p}
- Paul
{p} {p}
